@807  = ~(You start to blush, as she points toward you) Well, laughing boy there slipped on the manure, and just as the cow was slipping, it landed on him. He broke poor Nessie's fall... and his ribs...~
@808  = ~And how did you see all this happen?~
@809  = ~You didn't think I would let him go without some supervision, did you? Needless to say, Dreppin came running in at all that ruckus... and after letting the priest see to his hurts, <CHARNAME> was given extra chores... you mucked stables out for three months, didn't you?~
@810  = ~(Tashia smiles, though there is also some gentleness that crosses her face) Don't worry. I will spare you from all the immediate jokes. I'm sure you heard them all back then, and you certainly don't need them now...~
@811  = ~(Her eyes seem shiny, as she finishes) But I always liked a man who could laugh at himself...~
@812  = ~(Tashia laughs, and she says) And just what sort of adornments did you have in mind?~
@813  = ~(Quickly searching the environs reveals a variety of other flowers, and soon you come back. You use the skills you have for making traps and snares for animals until you have an exquisite floral crown, vibrant with pink carnations, peach chrysanthemums, yellow lilies, and white roses, in your hand. The various flowers give off a heady perfume, and Tashia's eyes turn shiny when you hand her the flowery circlet.)~
@814  = ~(Tashia stops by a bush, a thin woody climbing plant slightly entwined the trunk of a small tree, yellow-green in color. After further examination, Tashia starts to pluck small bluish-purple crescent shaped, compressed berries, putting them in her belt pouch, before popping a few in her mouth, swallowing immediately, and her face contorts with disgust, and she immediately spits out the remnants, pouring the other fruits from her belt pouch.)~
@815  = ~(Jaheira, hearing the sound, looks over with interest) Tashia, just what is going on?~
@816  = ~(Tashia wipes her mouth of the foul acrid taste) Something is wrong with these grapes. Its even worse than biting into a lime.~
@817  = ~(Jaheira examines the bush in turn) Hmmm... well, first thing, there is nothing wrong with this bush.~
@818  = ~What do you mean there is nothing wrong?~
@819  = ~This is Moonseed. Its fruit looks like grapes, but they aren't. In small amounts it is actually a good laxative, as I'm sure you will find out.~
@820  = ~(Tashia clutches her sides, with an anxious look on her face) What do you mean, I will find out?~
@821  = ~Just be glad you didn't eat more than a small handful. It could cause purging.~
@822  = ~I said, what do you mean I will find out?~
@823  = ~(She smirks) Come, Tashia, I didn't think you were that hard of hearing. I said that it was a diarrhetic. I highly recommend that when you... leave, you keep an eye out for the poison sumac.~
@824  = ~(Tashia's face reddens slightly) Isn't there anything you can do to help me?~
@825  = ~(Jaheira shakes her head) No. One shouldn't use one's spells casually. Not when the matter will resolve itself. Let... Nature take its course.~
@826  = ~Move yer candy ass out of my way, long ears, or else ye will find me axe buried up to the hilt in yer skull...~
@827  = ~Oh, and why is that, you gnarled dirt-grubber?~
@828  = ~The answer be very simple, tree hugger. If I have to spend another minute with yer yammering without a protective layer of ale to fortify me, I shall start swinging me axe.~
@829  = ~You know, I could assist you by planting it in your pointy head.~
@830  = ~Ye better count yer blessings, bat-ears, that I be more thirsty for alcohol than blood at the moment.~
@831  = ~(Korgan sits down and proceeds to down several steins of ale.)~
@832  = ~Barkeep... two for me.~
@833  = ~And just what do ye think yer doing? ~
@834  = ~I'm just taking my refreshment here... got a problem with that, half-pint?~
@835  = ~Whatever... just don't stink up the bar with yer flowers.~
@836  = ~(As time passes, Korgan notices how much Tashia is putting away)~
@837  = ~Yer not doing too badly there for a la-dee-da flower kisser.~
@838  = ~Well, I have to have a way to keep the bile from rising into my mouth due to present company.~
@839  = ~At least ye got spirit, long ears, I'll grant ye that.~
@840  = ~Don't try to sweet talk me, Korgan. Tell you what... up for a friendly wager?~
@841  = ~And what's that?~
@842  = ~I got 100 gold pieces that says 'I can drink you under the table'.~
@843  = ~Har har! Are ye serious? If ye are, then put yer money where yer mouth is, girlie.~
@844  = ~(Tashia places her coins on the bar, Korgan matches it, and they both start to drink. Several hours pass, but by this point, their 'friendly' wager is forgotten, and in fact, they both start to sing, Korgan in a guttural bass, and Tashia in a high soprano)~
@845  = ~Do your balls hang low?
Do they wobble to and fro?
Can you tie them in a knot?
Can you tie them in a bow?
Can you throw them over your shoulder
Like a continental soldier?
Do your balls hang low?

Ting-a-ling, here's a lesson
That you best not be forgettin'
If you can't get it up for a lovin' session,
Tarragon and gingsing,
Will fortify your dink,
Do your balls hang low?~
@846  = ~Do your balls hang low?
Do they wobble to and fro?
Can you tie them in a knot?
Can you tie them in a bow?
Do they make a lusty clamor
When you hit them with a hammer?
Do your balls hang low?

Ting-a-ling, all you women
If you want some sexy sinnin'
Use your cotton sheets
Not your satin linen,
Cause you will get a lumpy head
From slipping off the bed,
Do your balls hang low?~
@847  = ~Do your balls hang low?
Do they wobble to and fro?
Can you tie them in a knot?
Can you tie them in a bow?
Do they have a hollow sound
When you drag them on the ground?
Do your balls hang low?

Ting-a-ling, its hot
And a beer would hit the spot
To be followed with a triple whiskey shot
But if you want to stick with beer
Hold your licker by the ears
Do your balls hang low?...~
@848  = ~Ooh, by the goddess... it feels like I got run over by a herd of cattle. Did anyone see the driver of that donkey cart?~
@849  = ~Okay, now where did I get this horned helmet?~
@850  = ~AAARGH! Where did these pink knickers come from!?!~
@851  = ~Hey Minsc, do they enjoy stories from where you are from?~
@852  = ~When the skalds stir to play, any true warrior of Rasheman heeds to their tales! Why, even Boo's righteous passion is quelled when they speak.~
@853  = ~Oh, I just want your opinion on a story. A man walks into an inn, and he orders a steak. The serving wench gave him a quick once over, and she said, 'I don't think so... you don't look like you can afford a glass of water, let alone a steak.' The guy nods in agreement, but replies, 'But what if I show you something that you haven't seen before, will you then give me my supper?~
@854  = ~Hmm... Boo says that one really should have the money to pay for their dinner.~
@855  = ~And Boo is one intelligent hamster. Now please let me continue... so, anyways, the waitress agrees and the man reaches into his pocket, and pulls out a tiny harpsichord and from the other a small hamster.~
@856  = ~Ooooh, this may be one of Boo's relatives. You didn't tell me you had a musician in the family.~
@857  = ~Yes, yes... well, the hamster starts to play up a storm and the waitress' eyes open wide, and she calls the innkeeper to come take a look. Everyone in the inn is now looking at the hamster, but the man reaches into a third pocket, and pulls out a green item... he places it on the counter, and everyone sees that it is a frog, and as the hamster plays, the frog starts to sing.~
@858  = ~A singing frog? Boo has never heard of such a one before.~
@859  = ~A wealthy merchant saw what was happening, and he said, 'How much for the frog and hamster?' The stranger shook his head, and said that the hamster wasn't for sale, but he could part with the frog for 300 gold pieces. As the greedy merchant went to his room, the waitress looked at the stranger, and asked, 'Are you insane? Giving up a singing frog for that much? It must have been worth thousands.' The stranger smiled, and he said, 'No, it wasn't. The hamster is a ventriloquist.~
@860  = ~A ventriloquist? Say it can't be so! The hamster is a foul thief! Boo's fur is all wiry in righteous anger! If we meet up with this deceptive rodent, we must apply the boots of justice to his backside!~
@861  = ~(Viconia glances appraisingly at Tashia) I wouldn't even give it a half a day...~
@862  = ~(sigh) Okay, Viconia, I give. Just what wouldn't take even half a day?~
@863  = ~It is nothing much, surfacer. I was just considering how long it would take to make you break on the rack...~
@864  = ~Oh, and you estimate that I wouldn't last even half a day? I'm so glad that you think so highly of me.~
@865  = ~Oh, don't act so insulted...~
@866  = ~That's right, isn't it. You participated in their bloodsports, didn't you? That explains it entirely.~
@867  = ~Believe it or not, I did find their practices distasteful, but when a matron mother is overlooking your shoulder, you learn quickly how long a victim will last. When to apply the last stroke of the lash, when to pull the last turn of the crank...~
@868  = ~You are quite proud of this, I take it?~
@869  = ~Of course, ibblith. I survived when many of my sisters did not, let alone many others. One who is not strong and adaptable soon finds themselves amongst the lower ranks, or discarded, like so much refuse.~
@870  = ~Well, I won't deny your strength. But for all the competition, all the strife, the drow are not exactly commanding too many surface kingdoms, now are they?~
@871  = ~That is true. Don't think I am foolish enough to disagree with the obvious. That constant conflict is also one of our greatest weaknesses. One doesn't need to be a tactical genius to see that. Our conflicts amongst ourselves does little to allow our power to be extended... and our treachery is so legendary that even normal enemies will band together to weaken us, bring us down if at all possible. But, even with all of this, it is a testament to our prowess that we still survive.~
@872  = ~(snort) Well, pardon me if I don't exactly sing the exploits of your prowess...~
@873  = ~Tashia, have I ever told you that you are coming quite nicely into your powers? Why, with just the proper instruction, I'm sure that you may even be worthy of being in my presence. (Yes, let's see how she reacts to my proposal.)~
@874  = ~Okay, Edwin, I'm just getting a bit tired, so I don't really have the energy to verbally joust with you. What are you getting at?~
@875  = ~Nothing, my dear, just stating the obvious. Why, with the proper training, as I just said, you could certainly deserve...~
@876  = ~You do realize that I'm not a proper wizard? Just how do you expect me to learn spells when all my magic comes from within?~
@877  = ~That's just it, Tashia... your power comes from within, it's as if you internalize all your spellbooks. Imagine what a wondrous advantage that is. Though it shames me to admit it, at times even I can see where that ability is greater than sheer memorization.~
@878  = ~(with a thoughtful glance on her face) The great Edwin, admitting shame? Okay, who are you, and what have you done to the real Edwin?~
@879  = ~Hear me out. It could be that as you grow stronger, the spells you display are founded on some internal desires. Why, if we could just channel that...~
@880  = ~And how would we channel that?~
@881  = ~Well, why don't you come to my bedroll this evening, and I will give you your first lesson.~
@882  = ~(Tashia bursts out in laughter) Edwin, I will give you some points for subtlety, at least for you. However,thanks, but no thanks. I'm afraid that you will have to sleep alone once more this evening.~
@883  = ~(Damn. So close, yes, so close...)~
@884  = ~(As the group walks along, the moon is bright in the sky, and Tashia's hair appears to glow in the darkness. Haer'Dalis gives out a small gasp, at this, and he walks toward her, a faraway stare in his eyes.)~
@885  = ~But, soft! what light through yonder window breaks?
It is the east...~
@886  = ~So help me, if you say, 'Tashia is the sun...' I shall kick you so far where the sun don't shine that my foot will be coming out of your mouth.~
@887  = ~Why, fair elf, do the words displease you?~
@888  = ~Only when they have been done to death. How often do you think that I can hear things like

O, speak again, bright angel! for thou art
As glorious to this night, being o'er my head

or some other such nonsense? I mean...sure, it may be a well turned phrase, but it gets boring after awhile...~
@889  = ~Forgive me, then. I was but complimenting your beauty--~
@890  = ~Why is it all bards always have to compliment a woman on her beauty? Why don't you guys try something original for a change. I mean, I'm sure even Milil gets tired of hearing the same thing day after day.~
@891  = ~Calm down, my swan...~
@892  = ~Every single time, it is usually some variation about a figure that won't quit. From there, the list expands to include skin like satin, hair of the softest gold, and a chest fit for a herd of cows. You think we like being described in a way similar to livestock?~
@893  = ~LTashia, you are taking this much too seriously!~
@894  = ~Oh really? Can I help it if it feels like you bards have some other agenda? It's almost always the woman who needs rescuing. It is always the woman who is the wicked stepmother. Either you guys want to keep us safe in a box, or bury us in one... six feet under.~
@895  = ~(Haer'Dalis looks at Tashia, and he beats a hasty retreat, muttering under his breath)~
@896  = ~You better not say 'that time of the month...' either.~
@897  = ~(Aerie walks up side by side with Tashia, a perplexed expression on her face. So drawn into thought, she accidentally bumps into her.)~
@898  = ~Oh, sorry Tashia...~
@899  = ~It's okay. Hmmm... just out of curiosity, would you mind telling me what is on your mind? You seem to be elsewhere, at least mentally.~
@900  = ~Oh, its nothing, or I don't think it is. It's just that as we left that last town, while everyone was busy getting supplies and everything, I was refilling our canteens when there was a man, eyeing the passing traffic. He might have been a thief, since he seemed to be taking in everything that went by. Anyways, he looked directly at me, and he seemed to get this weird... I hesitate at calling it a smile, but he gave this smile, walked over, grasped my hands, and said, 'I have faced powerful spirits, magical beasts, and evil men, but 'twas your eyes, milady, which finally smote me.~
@901  = ~And what did you do?~
@902  = ~What could I do? All I remember is that time seemed to stop, and I spent a lot of time looking down at my feet... and then I heard someone calling my name to keep up, and I hurried to catch up. But the man seemed bemused by my blush.~
@903  = ~(Tashia smiles, though there is a tight edge to it) Sounds like someone just tried a pick up line on you.~
@904  = ~A pick up...line?~
@905  = ~Yeah, that's where a stranger tries to talk with you, mainly because he finds you attractive and would like to get to know you better.~
@906  = ~But why? Why would someone try to talk to me in that way... at all? I mean... why would anyone...~
@907  = ~Not that women are to my taste, but I think the answer is very simple, Aerie. You are a beautiful woman... too be honest, I'm surprised that someone hasn't tried to be with you as it is.~
@908  = ~Funny. They may think that... but they don't know that I'm deformed, do they... ~
@909  = ~(Tashia sighs, as she realizes that Aerie is about to go into another bout of self-pity, and rapidly changes the subject to head it off.)~
@910  = ~At least you had a decent first line... mine was much worse.~
@911  = ~What do you mean?~
@912  = ~How would you have reacted if someone told you 'Pardon me, madam, but your beauty has caused an involuntary lowering of my drawbridge. If I show you where the handle, is can you crank it back up?~
@913  = ~(Aerie blushes furiously) Oh my...~
@914  = ~Say Tashia, you may have heard of my deeds with the Hillgnasher Giants. But have you also heard...~
@915  = ~Anomen, give it a rest already.~
@916  = ~Something wrong, milady?~
@917  = ~I'm sure I'm not the only one that has felt this way, and I'm sure that you are probably correct in your deeds. Indeed, if true, then there is reason to be proud... but that doesn't mean you should be so boastful about it.~
@918  = ~Me, boastful? Those are harsh words, my lady. How can it be boasting when it is simply the truth?~
@919  = ~Truth or not, but that seems to be the only thing coming out of your mouth. As I already said, there is nothing wrong with taking pride in your deeds, but if that is the only thing that you can talk about, then you live a mighty empty life. Frankly, its a wonder...~
@920  = ~(Anomen splutters, and interrupts) If that is the case, then why is it that most of the ladies back in Amn hung on my very word?~
@921  = ~Well, as it is unlikely I'll be able to hobnob around the rich and famous, I can only hazard a guess or two. But the first is that some of them were genuinely interested...~
@922  = ~But, you just said...~
@923  = ~Of course I said that it sounds very arrogant to talk of your exploits time after time, but that doesn't mean others don't find them fascinating. Have you considered the circumstances of the average woman of nobility?~
@924  = ~Consider...?~
@925  = ~(sighs) The average noblewoman tends to lead a very boring life, compared to the men, anyways. Unless they have an understanding father, or are strong enough to set out on their own. There is a very small range of allowable behavior for them. You don't see too many noble ladies taking up a life of adventuring, now do you?~
@926  = ~Well, no...~
@927  = ~Of course not. I mean, it seems to me that a woman is mainly expected to solidify social connections, and assure the next generation of nobles. Hell, even ones that are into horse riding, hunting, or falconry are looked down on just a bit as well.~
@928  = ~You are right...~
@929  = ~Anyways, to get back to my point... when you tell your stories - and you do tell them rather energetically and vividly at that, even if it gets old after a while of the same thing - you draw them into in, and for a brief moment, you show them a life that doesn't bind them.~
@930  = ~But then, what am I supposed to tell them... afterwards?~
@931  = ~(Tashia pauses thoughtfully) Tough nut there, I admit. I mean, when I think of women of 'high station', I get images of obsessive weavers and compulsive dressmakers in mind. Maybe you can break the ice with a joke...~
@932  = ~A joke? Surely you jest!~
@933  = ~(winces) And I would stay away from the bad puns...~
@934  = ~So you're Imoen! I'm pleased to meet you. To be honest, I was wondering whether you really were alive or not.~
@935  = ~Heh, well, I was wondering what was keeping <CHARNAME>... its not like <PRO_HIMHER> to be so late.~
@936  = ~(Tashia smiles, then changes the topic so as not to bring up some recent unpleasant memories) Heh, you know, you remind me of my younger sister.~
@937  = ~Really, I do? Younger sister, huh. Just how many brothers and sisters did you have?~
@938  = ~(she smiles, thinking of pleasant memories) There were five of us altogether. We were orphans really, but one family took us in. Heh, sometimes I wonder what possessed my foster parents to take us all in.~
@939  = ~Just like <CHARNAME> and I with Gorion. Well, truth be known, mainly me. Not that <PRO_HESHE> didn't have <PRO_HISHER> moments, but <PRO_HESHE> was always more serious of the two of us.~
@940  = ~Yeah, you know. I remember back... oh, I must have been about 12... anyways, with so many kids there, money could get to be quite tight. Well, my older brother, Ilyan, had this great idea that would save us time and money. When we weren't doing chores around the house or anything like that, Ilyan usually was drafted to watch us, being the oldest of us all. But he also loved fishing. It wasn't until he got the rest of us hooked that we were able to supplement the dinner table. Anyways, Ilyan got the idea that instead of constantly trying to catch fish for the table, it would be better for us to raise our own.~
@941  = ~I think I see where this is heading...~
@942  = ~Of course. So, one day while our foster parents went to town to sell our produce and such, we all went out back and dug a big hole. Probably wasn't no more than 5 feet wide, maybe 3 feet deep, but it seemed like it was much larger. That's a lot of dirt for a group of kids to move. Anyways, we then took buckets of water and started filling it. Anyways, we were about done when our foster parents came in. Well, nothing more happened, dinner was served and whatever. Anyways, it starts to get late, and so we go to bed. The sun had just set, and our foster father needed to go use the privy... did I mention it's an outdoor privy? Next thing we know, we hear screaming and swearing coming from outside, and our foster father is busy bellowing for us all to come down.~
@943  = ~I gather you didn't keep your ditch?~
@944  = ~Of course not. You see, once he calmed down, our foster-father said that since we liked digging so much, we could muck out the barn. I swear, we couldn't get rid of the odor for a week from our clothes.~
@945  = ~Mazzy, may I ask a question?~
@946  = ~Sure you may. In fact, I think you just did.~
@947  = ~(her lips cracking slightly) Why Mazzy, a joke... I didn't think you had it in you.~
@948  = ~(Mazzy smiles) Well, I may not be as adept as you at constructing a fair turn of phrase, Tashia, but that doesn't mean I can't appreciate a well crafted phrase.~
@949  = ~Oh, it's like anything else, I imagine. Whatever you put your mind to, you can usually learn.~
@950  = ~Yes, although I can understand the urge of a crowd if a jester gets up there and starts asking, 'Why do knights ride stallions in the day?' and the inevitable reply is, 'Because they don't like nightmares'. Anyways, you said you wanted to ask me something?~
@951  = ~Yes, I did. Well, with all that we've been through, it seems like I'm using my magic more and more. And with that period in Trademeet... well, would it be possible for you to help me get my staff work back up to par?~
@952  = ~Sure, Tashia, I wouldn't mind... but are you sure? I'm sure there are plenty of others in the party that could help you just as easily.~
@953  = ~No, there really isn't. The last time I asked for help, the fool put his arms around me, and grabbing the staff with both hands said, 'Fighting is like everything else : it's all in your thrust...~
@954  = ~(winces) I hope you put the churl in his place.~
@955  = ~Well, last I heard, they managed to find a cleric good enough. But walking with a dislocated kneecap has to be painful...~
@956  = ~Ouch!~
@957  = ~Tashia, quiet. Too much shouting distracts even me from listening for possible trouble...~
@958  = ~That's easy for you to say. Tall, dark, handsome, and brooding...~
@959  = ~What do you mean by that?~
@960  = ~You heard what I said. (Tashia lifts her arm slightly, and where her other hand is applying pressure, you see it starting to swell and redden. She almost jerks her arm away from Valygar when he reaches out to look at it.)~
@961  = ~Tashia, if you don't stop that this instant, I can't see what's wrong. I don't bite, you know.~
@962  = ~(Further examination reveals that there is a bee sting on Tashia's arm, and carefully, taking water from his canteen, he cleans the area thoroughly, and then with the flat edge of his dagger, removes the stinger.)~
@963  = ~(Tashia's face flinches slightly, and she barely rasps out, her eyes watering, giving a dry cough) Just what are you doing?~
@964  = ~(Tashia gives one more shriek, as Valygar pulls her down to the ground, making her lie flat, and he partially tears open her blouse, laying his hands on her shoulders. Tashia starts to tremble under Valygar's hands, her eyelids fluttering rapidly, and she starts to jerk as Valygar's own eyes start rolling in back of his head, and he whispers something deep under his breath.)~
@965  = ~(Almost as fast as the seizures set in, they slowly start to subside, and Valygar wearily rises to his feet, pulls his clothing around him, and he goes back to keeping a lookout for any possible danger.)~
@966  = ~Give her some air. She will be wanting water. Just give it to her in sips...~
@967  = ~(Slowly, Tashia stabilizes, and as she leans back weakly, she rasps out) You saved me... what... happened?!?~
@968  = ~You went into shock. Looks like you're allergic to bee stings.~
@969  = ~Shock? Allergic? I've been stung before. I've never... it felt like my whole body was on fire.~
@970  = ~Tashia, I know what I am speaking of. Some people are allergic to bees. It can kill, sometimes very quickly. I don't really know why, but I also know that sometimes people have been stung before with no problems, but one sting later...~
@971  = ~Valygar...~
@972  = ~If you are well enough to talk, well, then you are well enough to walk.~
@973  = ~(Sparing a few more glances, he softens slightly) Take a few more minutes...~
@974  = ~(Once the party gets moving again, Tashia strides up to his side, and she quietly says) Valygar, thank you...you saved my life.~
@975  = ~You're welcome, it was nothing. Now, can we get back to the trail?~
@976  = ~After you answer me one question...~
@977  = ~Hmm?~
@978  = ~I know you healed me, and I know how you feel about magic. So... why?~
@979  = ~First of all, its not magic. Well, it is, but it isn't. I mean, as a ranger, its not a major secret, but we are endowed with some minor abilities, no different than a cleric, really.~
@980  = ~Yes, but I still know how you feel about...~
@981  = ~Tashia, what will it take for you to drop this? Would it be so hard to believe that I don't hate all magic-users? Even I can slowly revise my opinions, but that doesn't mean I still don't think the temptation of power is too great for one to pursue magic, but neither will I let my comrades down.~
@982  = ~Okay, I will leave it be.~
@983  = ~Hey Yoshimo, I am curious. You're not from around here, are you?~
@984  = ~Indeed I am not, Tashia. Tell me, what gave it away? Was it my accent... or was it my swarthy, if rather handsome appearance? Maybe it was...~
@985  = ~(She laughs) Okay, okay... I kinda walked right into that one. Tell me, though, where are you from? I come from the lands of the Ten Towns, much further to the north. One thing I can say I don't honestly miss too much is the constant cold.~
@986  = ~A man in my line of work must be a bit careful who they tell information to... but you seem honest enough. Truth be known, I come from Kara-Tur.~
@987  = ~Kara-Tur? Funny, you don't sound how I would imagine one from Kara-Tur would sound like.~
@988  = ~Oh? And just how would you expect us to sound? Not all of us go around sounding like we are speaking in broken phrases like. If I went around saying things like:

Autumn winds dance in the sky
The leaves fall frosted with ice
The swallows return south

I could guarantee that half of my business would be cut as they waded through the swamp of my language.~
@989  = ~Yeah, heh. I guess I really should have given it some thought. But coming to Amn, isn't that a bit out of the ways to go to from Kara-Tur?~
@990  = ~Indeed it is. I spent many a night aboard ship, too many nights it felt like sometimes. Though I was glad to make landfall... as was the crew.~
@991  = ~Really? And why that would be?~
@992  = ~Oh, it had a little something to do with their gambling debts. Why, I bet that if I would have had one more week, I would have been the proud owner of a large, if smelly fishing trawler.~
@993  = ~And just what would you have done with that ship?~
@994  = ~I don't know. Maybe turn it into a riverboat gambler... one that reeks of dead fish.~
@995  = ~Hey Tashia, did you ever hear...~
@996  = ~Let me guess, Jan, this is going to be some pointless story about one of your myriad relatives. It shall go on and on, without any end in sight, involving some kind of small, vaguely round vegetable?~
@997  = ~Tashia, you cut me to the quick. Why, this story doesn't involve anything that you just said.~
@998  = ~Okay, Jan, what is it, then?~
@999  = ~As I was going to say, I was going to ask if you ever heard of my cousin Bjorn. Rather good with his hands, expert locksmith. Anyways, there was this king who was going off to war. Unsure how long he would be, and worried about the... fidelity of his new wife, he commissioned Bjorn to create a chastity belt.~
@1000 = ~Heh, as if that would stop a truly determined lady.~
@1001 = ~Normally, it wouldn't. However, I did say that Bjorn was an expert locksmith. When the king came to see Bjorn's creation, he was rather surprised to find a rather large hole in the most obvious of places. That which a chastity belt was meant to guard against.~
@1002 = ~Really? I would think that an opening at that... orifice would rather defeat the whole purpose of having the belt.~
@1003 = ~Indeed. But I did say that was Bjorn rather resourceful. Upon seeing the king's disbelief, Bjorn reached over the workbench for his lunch, and pulled out a rather large turnip. He slid the turnip into the gaping hole, which resulted in a whistle in the air, and a satisfying snick. Pulling his hand back, Bjorn showed that half of the turnip was cut clear in half, and pointing at the hole, revealed a rather sharp blade.~
@1004 = ~Ouch...~
@1005 = ~Certainly. Anyways, the king was well pleased with Bjorn's invention, and he doubled the salary he was paying my cousin. Of course, as he had no intention of paying him anything, Bjorn spent the next few years in the dungeon. Anyways, the king finally came back from his years at war and assembled his knights. He had them drop their drawers for an inspection, and much to his chagrin, everyone of them was mutilated in some fashion... all but one knight, his brother actually.~
@1006 = ~I think I see where this is going.~
@1007 = ~Oh yes. The king embraced his brother in a manly hug, pleased that at least one man was loyal to him. The king smiled, saying, 'Since you were the only one who kept faith with me, I shall reward you with anything you want. All you have to do is say what you want.' Several minutes passed, as his brother turned his head, and the king said, 'Come, come. No need to be bashful... all you have to do is give voice to it.~
@1008 = ~I should have seen this coming...~
@1009 = ~So the brother opens his mouth, and says, 'Ah-buh-buh-ah-buh-buh'~
@1010 = ~... Jan?~
@1011 = ~Yes, Tashia?~
@1012 = ~Go away.~
@1013 = ~(As the group travels along, Tashia notices that Nalia is a bit quiet, keeping her eyes to the ground, only raising them up when she senses the group makes a change in their direction.)~
@1014 = ~Hey Nalia, what's so interesting on the ground?~
@1015 = ~Oh, hi Tashia. No, there is nothing. Why do you ask?~
@1016 = ~No reason, really, just that you seem a bit preoccupied. I thought maybe you found a trail of breadcrumbs or something to follow.~
@1017 = ~Trail of bread... oh, that old story of the woodcutter's children putting down a trail of breadcrumbs to follow their way home. No, I was just thinking.~
@1018 = ~Thinking about what Isaea said? I won't deny that I wish matters had been settled more definitely, but I also know these things take time.~
@1019 = ~There is that. But that wasn't what I was thinking of, it's just... I don't think I can repay anyone for all that has happened.~
@1020 = ~What do you mean, repay?~
@1021 = ~Well, it was easy when you all defeated the trolls. After they were defeated, I gave you your gold as a reward. But you saving me from Isaea... I don't know that if there is any way I can pay you all back anytime soon.~
@1022 = ~Nalia... whoever said anything about paying us back?~
@1023 = ~What? Did I say something wrong? I'm sorry, but I guess you guys don't really know me all that well. But I do repay my debts.~
@1024 = ~I am sure that you do, Nalia. But this isn't about repaying debts, not like that.~
@1025 = ~What do you mean? Well, if you guys want something else, I could probably find something else. Sell a few heirlooms...~
@1026 = ~No, Nalia. We didn't do any of that because we expected recompense, we did that because we were friends. Well, I can't speak for any of the others, I guess... but I'm sure <CHARNAME> did it for the same reason I did: that we don't like something hurting our friends.~
@1027 = ~Friends?~
@1028 = ~Yes, Nalia, friends. Is that so hard to believe? I would like to think we are friends.~
@1029 = ~Friends... we are friends, aren't we?~
@1030 = ~Certainly.~
@1031 = ~Friends. I didn't really have friends, growing up that is. Oh, there was Baunchy and such, but he was really Father's friend. Aunty ruined any friends I might have made with the commoner kids, always going on a tirade about how I was ruining myself and Father. Well, I loved him of course... but ever since mother died, Father threw himself into his business more than anything else. And whatever Aunty wanted, he gave her, just to keep her out of earshot.~
@1032 = ~I'm sorry.~
@1033 = ~Don't say it. Don't say you're sorry when you had nothing to do with it.~
@1034 = ~But I know what you meant, and I thank you for it.~
@1035 = ~So, Tashia, what do friends tend to talk about?~
@1036 = ~Whatever comes to their mind actually. Heh, why I remember talking with my sister. You know that I had five siblings... we originally went traveling together. Anyways, she had this crush on the boy. I thought he was a bit slow myself, but I must admit, he was easy on the eyes...~
@1037 = ~Did you just growl, Viconia?~
@1038 = ~Not at you, iblith, but since you already had the temerity to broach on my thoughts, let me ask you this. How do you tolerate it?~
@1039 = ~Tolerate what? Your gripes and complaints? It isn't easy, but given enough time, even Ilmater would learn to tune you out.~
@1040 = ~I would have you flayed for such disrespect back home...~
@1041 = ~But you aren't back home.~
@1042 = ~And that is part of the problem...and a lesser concern. No, what I am asking is why you surface women allow men to continue with this nonsense of thinking they are even your equals, let alone your betters.~
@1043 = ~Hmm. I don't see it that way myself, not entirely. On the other hand, I know there are plenty of women who would agree with you.~
@1044 = ~Sounds like there may be sensible surfacers after all.~
@1045 = ~I know one who is fond of saying, 'Men are like fine wine. They start out as sweet as grapes, then women must stomp on them and keep them in the dark, until they mature into something nice to have dinner with.~
@1046 = ~Ah, she would have made a good drow, unlike simpering dolts like you. Males aren't worth much until properly broken in.~
@1047 = ~Perhaps. But I would have to disagree with you. What about love? What about trust? Your way... you may live, but it would be lonely.~
@1048 = ~L'alurl abbil zhah dosstan. The only one you can trust is yourself. Everything else is foolish sentimentality.~
@1049 = ~Yoshimo, would you say you are a good bounty hunter?~
@1050 = ~Good enough, for Yoshimo stands before you, does he not? He didn't die of starvation for losing his quarry, nor does he lie in some forgotten alley, a knife in his back.~
@1051 = ~Heh, ask a stupid question...~
@1052 = ~Was there a particular reason you asked me that question?~
@1053 = ~Actually, there was another one I wanted to ask, but was unsure how to phrase it. Ever since we've met, you seem confident of your abilities, and for good reason. I was just curious if there was a time or two when your quarry got the better of you.~
@1054 = ~You honor me with your praise, but you are right that not all my hunts have been successful. Take my fourth assignment... no, it was the fifth assignment as an example. I was hired to find someone who owed my principal a great deal of money.~
@1055 = ~I expect you probably had to chase him into the woods or something.~
@1056 = ~No, not really. You see, the man I was looking for actually worked a couple towns over as a tea-master at a local shrine. I pretended to make a social call on my quarry, and was invited to tea.~
@1057 = ~Invited to tea? Why would you be invited to tea?~
@1058 = ~It is a ceremony common to those parts, and no disrespect intended Tashia, the significance of which may be lost on you. As I said, I was invited to tea. Little did I know how proficient my quarry was at his craft. Upon my entrance, the tea-master knew something was amiss, and politely asked me to leave my sword outside for the ceremony.~
@1059 = ~I gather it didn't exactly go down that way? Let me guess, you refused and then there was one splattered tea-master lying on the ground of the shrine.~
@1060 = ~You rush the tale, but no, events didn't unfold the way you surmised. You were correct in assuming I kept my sword by my side. As I explained to the tea-master, I was a warrior, and would never be parted from my blade. The tea-master nodded sagely, and invited me in, sword and all. The tea pot started to whistle...and the tea-master suddenly tipped it over. Hissing steam rose and filled the room with smoke and ashes.~
@1061 = ~And the tea-master ducked out in the ensuing clamor?~
@1062 = ~That was my first thought. So I ran outside to find him--only to find he wasn't there, nor was my sword. Turning around, I saw the tea-master still in the teahouse. He bowed before me, and said, 'It was my mistake. Come back in and have some tea. I have your sword covered with ashes, and will clean it and give it back to you.'~
@1063 = ~So what did you do afterwards?~
@1064 = ~There was little else I could do, but go back and enjoy my tea.~
@1065 = ~(sigh)~
@1066 = ~What's wrong, Tashia?~
@1067 = ~Oh, it's nothing. Melancholy mostly. Nothing serious.~
@1068 = ~Are you sure? We can talk about it if you wish.~
@1069 = ~Well, it's just that today was my stepmother's birthday. She took us in, my stepbrothers and stepsisters, I mean. Heh, of course, it used to drive me nuts trying to find a gift that she didn't already have, or one my siblings got for her.~
@1070 = ~Heh, I know the feeling. It wasn't much different back at Candlekeep. Why, on Gorion's birthday... no, maybe it would be better not to say anything.~
@1071 = ~You already mentioned it, Imoen. You can't hold back now.~
@1072 = ~I guess I can't, at that. Well, you have to understand, there weren't very many children at Candlekeep, and so we were under the care of various researchers and teachers. As a result, we didn't exactly have much leeway in gifts.~
@1073 = ~I can see where that would be a problem.~
@1074 = ~You don't know the half of it. Anyways, it was Gorion's birthday, and it was a big to do. One kid, he was studying under the priest of Oghma, brought forth a box, and Gorion shook it, saying, 'I know what it is. I bet it is a book.' The boy said, 'That's right'. Then one of the scullery maids came with a box, and Gorion held it up, and said, 'I bet I know what it is. Is it candy?' 'That's right' said the maid.~
@1075 = ~And then it was your turn?~
@1076 = ~Yes, it was. Anyways, I gave my box to Gorion, and he noticed it was leaking. He touched a drop with his finger and tasted it. 'I bet I know what it is,' he said, 'is it wine?~
@1077 = ~Wine?~
@1078 = ~Well, I was staying with Winthrop at the time. He was the innkeeper at Candlekeep, as well as the chief bartender.~
@1079 = ~Which is why Gorion would guess there was wine in it.~
@1080 = ~Except that it wasn't wine. Imagine Gorion's surprise when he found a puppy within.~
@1081 = ~Stop it!~
@1082 = ~Stop what?~
@1083 = ~Yer getting that beetle-like look on yer bleeding face, pointy-ears, and I don't like it.~
@1084 = ~By the gods, I have no idea what you are babbling about, Korgan.~
@1085 = ~Ye don't? I donnae believe you. Every time yer ears twitch, and yer face scrunches up like a used up dish rag, ye then have to spout off yer latest riddle or some other twaddle.~
@1086 = ~Well, I hate to disappoint you, gritsucker, but I wasn't thinking about that. Truth be known, I was thinking of someone else... someone you reminded me of.~
@1087 = ~And who would this poor sod be?~
@1088 = ~Ever heard of Gordian Knotbreaker? He lived a long time ago, but was considered one of the greatest riddle solvers ever lived.~
@1089 = ~I told ye that I dinnae want to hear clap-trap on any riddles.~
@1090 = ~And you won't, not really. You see, he lived in a time when his country was engulfed by ruin and revolt. The high king had died, and no legitimate heir had been found. In despair, the priests prayed with all their might for an answer to their problems.~
@1091 = ~Yer boring me, girlie, and I still be needing to sharpen me axe. Perhaps I will use yer skull.~
@1092 = ~The next morning, a massive knot was found on the altar along with a scroll saying that whoever could undo the knot was the rightful ruler.~
@1093 = ~Picking a king by whoever could undo a knot? Ye got to be joking.~
@1094 = ~That was the way it was, though. So everyone came to try and untie the knot. They found no end to the knot so they could untie it, and magic proved ineffective. Not until Gordian came up, you see. He spat in his hands, picked up his axe...~
@1095 = ~And cut the priests off at the knees?~
@1096 = ~And cut the knot in half, thereby becoming king.~
@1097 = ~Finally, someone who didn't have his head up his bloody arse!~
@1098 = ~Well, sometimes the best solution is the direct one.~
@1099 = ~Cernd, are there any civilized comforts you miss since you've become a druid?~
@1100 = ~My needs are few and far between. If I am hungry, I can either hunt something down, or go gathering plants. I never feel lonely, for all of nature's creatures are there to keep me company.~
@1101 = ~But needs aren't the same as comforts, are they?~
@1102 = ~No, they are not. I admit there are a couple things that I do miss.~
@1103 = ~Such as?~
@1104 = ~(runs a hand along his cheek) Mirrors for one. Razors for another. Do you know how hard it is to keep oneself clean shaven when you only have your reflection in a pond, and a scimitar or dull knife to scrape away the hair?~
@1105 = ~Ugh, I can see where that would be a problem. Not to mention all the blood...~
@1106 = ~Well, I looked more like a wounded boar after the first time I shaved. The...wound...was attended to, but the healer was tempted to leave it be as an object lesson. Still, it was better than the alternative.~
@1107 = ~Alternative?~
@1108 = ~There was another druidess who said she found a way to keep hair from growing entirely.~
@1109 = ~I hope it didn't involved any kind of potions or creams. My step-father, in a moment of vanity, bought an elixir from a traveling gnome one time. His hair grew alright, but it was the hair between his ears.~
@1110 = ~No, it was nothing like that. No, the druidess said by applying a light electrical jolt to a region a certain number of times, it would kill the hair that grew there, keeping it smooth all year round.~
@1111 = ~Ouch. Surely no one was stupid enough to get it done.~
@1112 = ~Not to my knowledge, no.~
@1113 = ~So Haer'Dalis, did you practice much to become the man mothers warn their daughters of, or does it come naturally?~
@1114 = ~You cut me to the quick with such an unwarranted jab. Why the hostility?~
@1115 = ~Excuse me, then. It's just that you remind me of my... former leman.~
@1116 = ~At least it is nice to know the resentment you harbor isn't entirely of my making. Still, I am curious, what is it about my manner that sets you most at unease?~
@1117 = ~If you really want to know, it is your silver tongue.~
@1118 = ~Then I think I see the problem. You were but an innocent maid, when your beau came into your life, and spoke honeyed words.~
@1119 = ~(whispers) Your lips are like red wine, I should like to drink from them.~
@1120 = ~Your eyes are like sparkling pools, I should like to bathe in their beauty.~
@1121 = ~See what I mean?!? You even know the exact same lines.~
@1122 = ~If it is any solace, Tashia, know that the lines aren't that original. Your erstwhile paramour would have taken them from another source. Why, I can easily think of at least three major works in which those lines are quoted.~
@1123 = ~And I guess you could have come up with something better?~
@1124 = ~Well, it perforce would depend on my intent. As I have come to know you, I would know to appeal to your intellect, that part of you which enjoys riddles and wordplay, as well as appeal to your sense of joy. For example, if I was to recast the line, I might have said something along the lines of...~
@1125 = ~Your lips are like red wine, I should like to drink from them. Your eyes are like sparkling pools, I should like to bathe in their beauty. Your hair is like a field of golden wheat, I should like to cut it, thresh it, and bake it into muffins.~
@1126 = ~(laughs slightly) Silver tongue and a rapier wit, especially to bring me out of my mood. You are a dangerous man, Haer'Dalis.~
@1127 = ~One must play to one's audience, my swan.~
@1128 = ~Jan, where did your family get its green thumb?~
@1129 = ~You know about that, Tashia?~
@1130 = ~I think everyone back in Amn knows about it.~
@1131 = ~I knew that cousin Norvik couldn't be trusted. Get a little turnip juice into him, and he starts to run at the mouth. I swear, we didn't mean for gangrene to set in, but once it did, we couldn't throw it out. Waste not, want not...~
@1132 = ~Jan, what in the nine hells are you rambling about? I was talking about the tree you and your family lives in. I mean, the plant was still alive.~
@1133 = ~Oh, that. Well, it only requires a little TLC.~
@1134 = ~TLC?~
@1135 = ~Turnip, love, and care.~
@1136 = ~I should have known. I should have known.~
@1137 = ~You didn't strike me as the gardening type, Tashia. Look at those nails, they are more suitable for gouging out eyes than they are for digging up tubers. Now, turnip stroker... yes, you definitely would have a future there.~
@1138 = ~Turnip... stroker?~
@1139 = ~To achieve maximum growth...~
@1140 = ~Enough, I don't want to know anymore.~
@1141 = ~But you are the one that brought the subject up!~
@1142 = ~No... no I didn't! Whatever. Sheesh, all I wanted to know was how you got your plants to grow so well. That way, when I got back to the Ten Towns, I could tell my mother. She loves to garden, and is always looking for an edge.~
@1143 = ~Well, why didn't you say so in the first place? There is no secret. For tomatoes, it's best to expose yourself to them at least twice a day.~
@1144 = ~Expose... yourself?~
@1145 = ~Certainly. That way they turn red of embarrassment. Though I must warn you to be careful around cucumbers. My father did it, and quadrupled their size within the season.~
@1146 = ~Tashia, is everything alright?~
@1147 = ~What? Yes, yes everything is alright Aerie.~
@1148 = ~Are you sure? You seemed...preoccupied.~
@1149 = ~I...I will be fine Aerie. I was just thinking. Thinking and remembering.~
@1150 = ~About Arilistan?~
@1151 = ~I must have been talking in my sleep again, but yes, I was thinking about him.~
@1152 = ~If he brought you such pain, why do you think of him?~
@1153 = ~He was my first love, Aerie. That is something a woman never forgets. A person can have many loves, but the first one is always special, though not always in a good way.~
@1154 = ~If...if it would help, you can always talk to me.~
@1155 = ~I appreciate the offer Aerie, but this is something I'm going to have to muddle through on my own.~
@1156 = ~Okay Tashia, I will leave you be. However, even I know the hurts of the soul, the head, the heart can be more dangerous than the wounds of the body.~
@1157 = ~(she hugs Aerie) You're a good friend, Aerie. When...when I'm ready, I will tell you.~
@1158 = ~So, how did you do it Keldorn? How did you manage to stay married for so many years?~
@1159 = ~There is no secret, Tashia. Maria and I never went to bed angry.~
@1160 = ~That's it? Surely you had to have fights and arguments.~
@1161 = ~Aye, we did, but we always made up before going to bed. Of course, all was not always this way.~
@1162 = ~Oh?~
@1163 = ~I remember one particularly horrible argument, and we ended up not speaking to each other. It is childish in retrospect, but who said youth was ever level-headed? I had to wake early the next day, and not wanting to break the silence, I wrote a note to Maria: 'Please wake me at seven bells'.~
@1164 = ~You really wanted to win bad, didn't you?~
@1165 = ~Aye, that I did. Let's just say, I learned several things that night. First, sometimes it is better to concede than press a point. Second, Maria is more patient than I ever could be.~
@1166 = ~What happened?~
@1167 = ~I woke with the sun shining in my face and the sound of nine bells echoing in my ears. Furious, I jumped out of bed, ready to break my silence--only to see a piece of paper flutter off the bed.~
@1168 = ~Teehee, I think I like the way Maria thinks.~
@1169 = ~As you guessed, Maria wrote, 'It's seven bells. It's time to wake up' on the slip of paper.~
@1170 = ~(hums)Golden slumber kiss your eyes, smiles await you when you rise.
Sleep, do not cry, and I'll sing you a lullaby.~
@1171 = ~Tashia, please stop...~
@1172 = ~Care you know not, therefore sleep, while I o'er you watch do keep...~
@1173 = ~Damn it, stop it, Tashia!~
@1174 = ~What? What's wrong, Anomen?~
@1175 = ~That song! Why were you humming that song?~
@1176 = ~I was just thinking of my sister. She...she used to like that song. Mother used to sing it to her before bed.~
@1177 = ~Used to?~
@1178 = ~She...she died of the pox. I...I held her hand as she went to sleep. Mother cradled her...~
@1179 = ~Shh. It's alright. Tashia. Please forgive my outburst. Go ahead, and sing it. I shall keep silent.~
@1180 = ~Are you sure? I mean, you were really angry--~
@1181 = ~Proceed as you will. Maybe, someday, I will tell you of the gentlest, kindest woman I've known.~
@1182 = ~Looks like your... friend is going to be a while. The name is Aimilona Goldmantle, I'm partners with yon shopkeeper. He attends to the clothing, while the armor is my purview.~
@1183 = ~You have the look of adventurers about you, so I know your kind normally doesn't go in for such fripperies as these. However, if you are of an interest, I may have something that might strike your fancy.~
@1184 = ~(Aimilona points toward a rack where there is a white garment hanging on a rack. As you come closer to examine it, you see that it is in fact a snow-white fur, the pelt unblemished by any other color, the front legs of it forming a neck clasp, an untarnished cloak.)~
@1185 = ~It came from a winter wolf. (She lifts an edge of the pelt, beckoning you to touch it. As your hand explores the fur, you find that the pelt is among the softest materials you've ever touched.)~
@1186 = ~Handworked... took about a month to soften. However, care was also taken to retain its resistance to the chill... definitely waterproof. Normally it would go for... 15,000 gold pieces... but it would stay here until the winter, and I would prefer to have the free space. I can let it go for as cheap as 12,000 gold pieces.~
@1187 = ~Hmm. It is an excellent cape, I will grant you, but that is a large amount of funds to come up with on a moment's notice, and who knows when I will be back this way. Tell you what, I will give you 10,000 gold pieces.~
@1188 = ~Well, that is a lot of money, but Tashia is worth every gold piece. Aimilona, you have a deal.~
@1189 = ~I'm sorry, friend, but that is much too high. I'm afraid I'm unable to pay for that amount now.~
@1190 = ~I'm sorry, but I can't go any lower than my initial offer. Take it or leave it...~
@1191 = ~All right then, I'll take it.~
@1192 = ~Sorry, I can't afford that.~
@1193 = ~It's good doing business with you, sir. I hope you enjoy the cloak.~
@1194 = ~By the way, if in the future you would like additional adornment, I am quite capable of enhancing the original. It didn't make sense to do so if no one was going to purchase it, but I am more than willing to work further on it... just bring me the proper materials, and for a price, it will be better than new.~
@1195 = ~Well, if you change your mind, it will be here for a bit longer, but I can make no guarantee that it will be here.~
@1196 = ~Welcome back, good sir! So, have you changed your mind about the pelt? Still a steal at the reasonable price of 12,000 gold pieces.~
@1197 = ~Not today. I'm just passing through.~
@1198 = ~That's why I'm here. Here's your money.~
@1199 = ~12,000 gold is still too high for a scrap of skin.~
@1200 = ~I'm sorry, but I can't go any lower than my initial offer. Take it or leave it.~
@1201 = ~It's good doing business with you, sir. I hope you enjoy the cloak. Also, I would be remiss in mentioning that if you are so inclined, we can include additional fripperies which improve on the base cape. Available for a modest fee, of course.~
@1202 = ~Very well, I shall put it back. If you return this way, it may still be here. However, I can guarantee that as the colder months come closer, it will be gone.~
@1203 = ~Welcome back, good sir! I trust there is nothing wrong with your purchase? Maybe it slipped my mind at the time, but all sales are final.~
@1204 = ~I didn't mean to come back here.~
@1205 = ~You mentioned something about improving the cloak?~
@1206 = ~Ah, you just took a wrong turn. It happens to the best of us. Why, when the road of life seems to be just one off-beaten path by another, sometimes it takes something special to set it straight. Let me tell you about a book that changed my life, my friend...~
@1207 = ~Indeed I did. Truth be known, what you possess is actually the lower end, more affordable winter cloak. Some of our more upper-scale clientele, however, demand accoutrement more befitting of their status. You will find that after our treatment of the fur, it offers the same protection as light armor, but is still as soft and pliable to the touch. Not only that, but the wearer of such a garment finds the cloak has captured the very touch of winter in its folds--which can be released at a later point.~
@1208 = ~Of course, the craftsmanship involved in creating such an item is such that we can only make it when the proper buyer gives proper payment. However, for the low price of 30,000 gold, you can own the Winter Cloak. I must warn you, though, due to the labor and materials involved, we can't haggle on the price.~
@1209 = ~No price is too high. I will get it.~
@1210 = ~30,000 gold? That's too rich for my blood.~
@1211 = ~Are you sure there is no way to lower the price?~
@1212 = ~Very good, sir. That is an attitude I can approve of. Here is your cloak. If by chance you find the enchantments failing, you can bring it back within thirty days for a refund.~
@1213 = ~I'm sorry to hear you think the price is too high. I bid you good day. If you change your mind, you know where to find me.~
@1214 = ~I apologize sir, but as mentioned, the cost can't be haggled down. The interplay of spells, as well as the raw cost of materials, and not to mention our resident enchanter's fees put it out of the range of all but the wealthiest of clients.~
@1215 = ~However, you also appear to be of an adventuring sort, so there just may be a way to defray the cost. We can't ignore our enchanter's costs, but if you could acquire the raw materials, you would find the costs definitely lessened... say, around the neighborhood of 7,500 gold pieces.~
@1216 = ~See, to guarantee the required amount of defense, the most basic amulet of protection is used in the making of the cloak. Additionally, the cloak gains its cone of cold capabilities through the sacrifice of a wand of frost. To channel all the magical energies properly, we use a perfectly cut diamond.~
@1217 = ~I will have to return when I find all you're looking for.~
@1218 = ~What do you know, I already have them.~
@1219 = ~I wish you luck on your quest then. Remember, you can always pay the extra amount if your searching doesn't yield the desired items.~
@1220 = ~Very, very good. I will just take those items from you, and we shall see about getting your enhanced cape back to you.~
@1221 = ~Another return visit? I must say I'm flattered, but I hope you realize that I'm already spoken for. Or are you back here on business?~
@1222 = ~I didn't mean to come here.~
@1223 = ~I have the money to buy the improvement of the cloak.~
@1224 = ~Well, I got everything you wanted.~
@1225 = ~Good day, sir. I hope you are enjoying your purchase.~
@1226 = ~(The shopkeeper runs a hand through his hair, a pleasant smile on his face) It was an honor to be outbid by m'lady. But I won't deny I hope it will be some time before you come this way again. My family needs to eat, after all...~
@1227 = ~You have taken too much already! You will return both Imoen's soul and Tashia!~
@1228 = ~And you have delivered on that promise. Return Tashia and perhaps I will be merciful.~
@1229 = ~I would have hunted you for your theft of Tashia alone. She is very important to me.~
@1230 = ~You place too much confidence in sentiment. The theft of Tashia will not save you.~
@1231 = ~An interesting ploy, though I am sure her fate will still serve as an example.~
@1232 = ~Here she is, though I doubt your fumbling could inspire the loyalty I take with a bite and a gaze. For all her words, her will was easier to break than a child's, as if craving the undeath in my touch.~
@1233 = ~You see? She's not even fully turned, but she is mine to command, and will obey when I send her against you now!~
@1234 = ~Yes, mistress... whatever you say.~
@1235 = ~Consider the needs of young Tashia here. It is so hard on your couples when you are separated.~
@1236 = ~I wasn't thinking of you losing him. This is a lesson, <CHARNAME>. Follow me and you will lose more than you could imagine. Starting now!~
@1237 = ~I have already lost one close to me, I refuse to lose another! When I am done with you, I shall scatter your ashes to the winds!~
@1238 = ~Is... is that you, <CHARNAME>? I...I was drowning in a tide of blood. I tried to scream, but the blood just flowed down my throat. I...I don't remember much except for the darkness that followed.~
@1239 = ~(She rushes toward you, wrapping her arms tightly around your body.)~
@1240 = ~I...I died again, didn't I? Twice...twice dead. And you saved me again. If...if I ever had any doubts about how you feel about me, they have been laid to rest.~
@1241 = ~Tashia, you won't get rid of me that easily.~
@1242 = ~Let's try to make sure third time isn't the charm, my love.~
@1243 = ~This is getting to be a habit, Tashia. I refuse to save you any more.~
@1244 = ~I don't think we can stay together, Tashia. Just being near me puts you in danger.~
@1245 = ~(Tashia gives a firm kiss on your cheek, and squeezes your hand) And I thank the gods for that.~
@1246 = ~(Tashia smiles wanly, though there is no humor in it) I know you were just trying to ease my despair, but pardon me if I don't laugh.~
@1247 = ~(Tashia's eyes open wide, and a look of hurt and anger floods her face. She reaches up, and smacks you hard, knocking you to the ground as magic augments her hand.)~
@1248 = ~You bastard! How could you say such a hateful thing? It's not like I planned this! Well, if that is how you feel about it, then I will spare you from worrying about me any further.~
@1249 = ~(Tashia's eyes widen, and a look of panic twists her features) That...that is a risk I'm willing to take! Please...please don't let the danger drive us apart.~
@1250 = ~Are you sure you wish to be with me?~
@1251 = ~I can't take that risk.~
@1252 = ~(Tashia's right hand locks desperately on your forearm, and when she speaks, it sounds like she has a sob caught in her throat.)~
@1253 = ~There will always be danger, <CHARNAME>. Even if you weren't a Bhaalspawn, an adventurer's life is far from safe. You could be the next one to die, not me. That is a danger we face...together.~
@1254 = ~(Tashia stiffens, and she steps away. When she speaks, her voice could freeze water.)~
@1255 = ~Then I shall spare your emotions. We shall be as strangers from this day forth.~
@1256 = ~Elhan!  I've the half vampire body of Tashia here because of you!  You'll tell me now!~
@1257 = ~A friend is afflicted by vampirism.  An old book suggested that followers of Oghma might know something about that.~
@1258 = ~Have you come seeking wisdom from the Binder of What is Known? The Wise God stands ready.~
@1259 = ~No, thank you, I have no need of help at the moment.~
@1260 = ~I lost a loved one in a battle with his sister, Bodhi.  I seek a means of curing her.~
@1261 = ~A loved one was taken by a vampire. What can I expect when I find them?~
@1262 = ~Someone I care about has fallen to a vampire. Is there any way to save them?~